nments: not only do they combat the terrorist Islamic Movement of Uzbekistan but also outlaw popular groups such as the Gülen movement. However, strong repression of religion might lead to radicalization.Kathrin Lenz-Raymann tests this hypothesis with an agent-based computer simulation and enriches her study with interviews with international experts, leaders of political Islam and representatives of folk Islam. She concludes that ensuring religious rights is essential for national security.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aFreedom of religionzAsia, Central. 4aAsia. 4aCentral Asia. 4aFreedom of Religion. 4aIslam. 4aIslamic Studies. 4aPolitical Ideologies. 4aPolitical Science. 4aPolitics. 4aSocial Movements. 4aTerrorism. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / General.2bisacsh  aAsia.  aCentral Asia.  aFreedom of Religion.  aIslam.  aIslamic Studies.  aPolitical Ideologies.  aPolitical Science.  aPolitics.  aSocial Movements.  aTerrorism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyterttranscript Complete eBook Package 2014z9783111025223oZDB-23-TGP08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyterttranscript English Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z97831106615520 cprintz978383762904040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/transcript.9783839429044?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783839429044zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783839429044/original  a978-3-11-064977-2 Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook P